I lovingly doubt selflessness. Lovingly being in doubt of selflessness does not mean I am in contempt of it. It means that I no longer allow my desire to be selfless to control my life for me. This does not mean that I am against all forms of self sacrifice. Self sacrifice is incredibly sexy when the person doing the sacrificing enacts it as a deliberate choice and not as a martyrdom that they live trapped in. I do not doubt selflessness because I think that we should all aspire and strive for success in the status quo. The reason I doubt selflessness is because I think that it often operates as an avoidance of grief. I think that we jump to selfless suffering when we think that giving ourselves up is faster or more convenient than mourning our own losses.

Season 2 finale episode of Voices on the Side with @alicesparklykat 💫

Ace is an astrologer and author who moved to the US from China as a young child. In this episode, we talk about the power and roots of names and how our respective Chinese and Korean cultures look to create harmony through the process of naming. We also talk about language systems, finding community, and of course — astrology. 

What I find particularly interesting about Ace’s perspective of astrology is the recognition that astrology was developed within colonialism, which comes with many aspects and meanings to be reckoned with, even within such a mythical, magical practice.

A note: This conversation was recorded in early October, and we make no mention of world events. Over the last 3 months, I have loved the way Ace has used their social media platform to speak up and to write about justice and liberation, and I invited them back onto the podcast for an updated conversation. That episode will go live later this month.
